<subSubSection pageId="32" pageNumber="33" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="32.[701,1228,1100,1750]" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">
DIAGNOSIS: Males can easily be recognized by the long, distally bent median apophysis (
<figureCitation box="[709,786,1309,1333]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="34.[151,198,1337,1359]" captionTargetBox="[128,1226,210,1294]" captionTargetId="figure-146@34.[128,1228,209,1303]" captionTargetPageId="34" captionText="Figs. 88–92. Zorocrates apulco, new species. 88. Left male palp, prolateral view. 89. Same, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5388249" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5388249/files/figure.png" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">fig. 89</figureCitation>
), females by the angular anterior epigynal margin and procurved posterior epigynal margins (
<figureCitation box="[913,990,1369,1393]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="34.[151,198,1337,1359]" captionTargetBox="[128,1226,210,1294]" captionTargetId="figure-146@34.[128,1228,209,1303]" captionTargetPageId="34" captionText="Figs. 88–92. Zorocrates apulco, new species. 88. Left male palp, prolateral view. 89. Same, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5388249" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5388249/files/figure.png" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">fig. 91</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="33" lastPageNumber="34" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="32.[701,1228,1100,1750]" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">
MALE: Total length 7. Coloration as in 
<taxonomicName genus="San" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" rank="species" species="blas">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Z. blas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Leg spination: femora: I p0-0-2, r0-1-1; II d1-1-0, p0-0-1, r0-2-1; III p0-1-1, r0-2-1; IV p0- 1-1, r0-0-2; patellae IV r0-1-0; tibiae: I d0-0-0, p0-1-0, v4-4-2; II d0-0-0, p1-0-0; III r1-0-1; IV d1-0-1; metatarsi: I p0-1-1, v2-2-2, r0-1-0; II p0- 1-1, r0-1-1; III r1-2-2. Cribellum small but apparently present. Retrolateral tibial apophysis short, recurved at tip; median apophysis greatly elongated, bent at right angle near tip, with small, proximally directed projection; tegular apophysis distally invaginated (
<figureCitation box="[1049,1173,1726,1750]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="34.[151,198,1337,1359]" captionTargetBox="[128,1226,210,1294]" captionTargetId="figure-146@34.[128,1228,209,1303]" captionTargetPageId="34" captionText="Figs. 88–92. Zorocrates apulco, new species. 88. Left male palp, prolateral view. 89. Same, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5388249" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5388249/files/figure.png" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">figs. 88–90</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5388245" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5388245" box="[112,1189,1228,1250]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5388245/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" startId="33.[112,159,1228,1250]" targetBox="[88,1185,210,1189]" targetPageId="33">
<paragraph blockId="33.[88,1189,1228,1276]" box="[112,1189,1228,1250]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
